Controlled and UnControlled Components:

1ï¸âƒ£ Whatâ€™s wrong in your current code
âŒ Issue 1: Ref usage is incorrect
----->unCntrlInput.current = "Uncontrol";

ğŸ‘‰ useRef does not store value directly like state.
IMP--->For uncontrolled inputs, ref.current points to the DOM element, not the value.

âœ… Correct way:
----->unCntrlInput.current.value

âŒ Issue 2: You used ref on a button instead of input
<button ref={unCntrlInput}>UN Controlled Button</button>


Uncontrolled components are inputs, not buttons.

âŒ Issue 3: No actual uncontrolled input exists

You only logged to console â€” but didnâ€™t read input from DOM.

2ï¸âƒ£ Correct Mental Model (VERY IMPORTANT)
ğŸ”¹ Controlled Component
React owns the data
Value comes from useState
Changes via onChange
<input value={state} onChange={...} />

ğŸ”¹ Uncontrolled Component
DOM owns the data
React accesses it only when needed
Uses useRef
<input ref={inputRef} />

3ï¸âƒ£ Correct & Clean Solution (BLOCK 3 â€“ Perfect)
This matches exactly what the task expects ğŸ‘‡

âœ… Final Working Code
import { useState, useRef } from "react";

const Test = () => {
  // Controlled
  const [controlledValue, setControlledValue] = useState("");

  // Uncontrolled
  const uncontrolledRef = useRef(null);

  const handleSubmit = () => {
    console.log("Controlled value:", controlledValue);
    console.log("Uncontrolled value:", uncontrolledRef.current.value);
  };

  return (
    <>
      {/* Controlled Input */}
      <input
        type="text"
        value={controlledValue}
        onChange={(e) => setControlledValue(e.target.value)}
        placeholder="Controlled Input"
      />

      <br />

      {/* Uncontrolled Input */}
      <input
        type="text"
        ref={uncontrolledRef}
        placeholder="Uncontrolled Input"
      />

      <br />

      <button onClick={handleSubmit}>Submit</button>
    </>
  );
};

export default Test;


